A peek under the hood — the ideas behind calcy, without the plumbing.

### It all runs on your device

calcy is a single web page with nothing behind it. Working out your sums,
handling uncertainty, saving your sheets — it all happens right here in your
browser. Nothing you type is sent anywhere.

### Units are part of the maths

Every quantity carries its units, and calcy keeps them consistent for you behind
the scenes. That's why `12 V / 4 ohm` comes out in amps, why conversions stay
exact, and why mixing things that don't belong together — metres and seconds —
gets flagged rather than fudged.

It copes with the awkward cases too. Temperatures add an offset rather than just a
scale. Decibels live on a logarithmic scale. Currencies are kept strictly apart so
they never mix by accident, and you can define your own exchange rates to convert
between them.

### Uncertainty is carried through, not bolted on

When a value is a range rather than a single number, calcy keeps track of the
whole spread as it flows through your calculation, so the final answer reflects
how unsure the inputs were. Reuse the same uncertain value twice and calcy
remembers it's the *same* value — so something like `x - x` comes out as exactly
zero, the way it should.

### Exact when it can be, estimated when it can't

This is the part most calculators skip. For familiar shapes — a bell curve, a
lopsided spread, a plain range — and operations that keep that shape, calcy uses
the exact textbook formula, so the average and the percentiles come back with no
guesswork at all. For everything else, it estimates the answer by running the
calculation many times across the range of possibilities and summarising what
comes out. You get the precise answer wherever one exists, and a dependable
estimate where it doesn't — without ever having to choose between them.

### The same numbers every time (until you ask otherwise)

Estimates start from a fixed point, so a sheet shows the same results each time
you open it. Press **Re-roll** when you want a fresh draw, to check that your
conclusion doesn't hinge on luck.

### Built to stay correct

The part of calcy that does the maths is checked relentlessly against thousands of
worked examples, so the answers you rely on stay correct as calcy grows.

No network, no tracking, no account. It's a calculator that happens to take
uncertainty seriously.
